ncient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adele Gournay was born about 1010, in Beaumont-les-Nonains, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ivo Bellomontensis de Beaumont. She died in 1099, at the age of 90."},"et":{"about 1010–1099":"umbes 1010–1099","1026–1059":"1026–1059","1040–1091":"1040–1091","1175–1237":"1175–1237","1010–1099":"1010–1099","1091":"1091","22 May 1059":"22. mai 1059","1237":"1237","Abt 1040":"umbes 1040","11 July 1091":"11. juuli 1091","1059":"1059","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1010":"1010","1175":"1175","about 1010":"umbes 1010","1040":"1040","Beaumont-les-N